jan Samaj Party\n| candidate  = [[Hemlata Chaudhary]]\n| votes      = 56,957\n| percentage = 34.54\n| change     = -\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| party      = Rashtriya Lok Dal\n| candidate  = Kawkab Hameed Khan\n| votes      = 49,294\n| percentage = 29.9\n| change     = -\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| party      = Samajwadi Party\n| candidate  = Sahab Singh\n| votes      = 41,584\n| percentage = 25.22\n| change     = -\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| party      =\n| candidate  = Remainder 11 candidates\n| votes      = 17,047\n| percentage = 10.33\n| change     = -\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n| votes      = 7,663\n| percentage = 4.65\n| change     = -\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n| votes      = 164,882\n| percentage = 62.58\n| change     = -\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|loser     = Rashtriya Lok Dal\n|winner  = Bahujan Samaj Party\n|swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bagpat district]]\n*[[Bagpat (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n*[[Sixteenth Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]]\n*[[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]\n\n{{Portal bar|India|Politics}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=40em}}\n{{Assembly constituencies of Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Assembly constituencies of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Bagpat district]]\n", "name_user": "MahakChaudhry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMember of the Legislative Assembly", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bagpat_(Assembly_constituency)"}
{"title_page": "Paul Kingsnorth", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Paul Kingsnorth\n| image         = Paul Kingsnorth.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Paul Kingsnorth in 2011\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1972}}\n| birth_place   = [[Worcester]], United Kingdom\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|1972|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Writer and thinker\n| education     = [[St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Novelist, writer, poet, environmentalist\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Kingsnorth''' (born 1972 in [[Worcester]]) is an English writer and thinker. He is a former deputy-editor of ''[[The Ecologist]]'' and a co-founder of the Dark Mountain Project. He lives in [[West Region, Ireland|the west of Ireland]].\n\n==Biography==\nKingsnorth spent his childhood in southern England with two younger brothers (one went on to work with [[Friends of the Earth]], the other for [[Citibank]]). His father was a passionate [[Thatcherite]], a businessman, and a mechanical engineer. Kingsnorth describes his father's background as \"working-class,\" and he says that his father pushed Kingsnorth to go to college. He was the first in his family to do so.<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\">{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Erica| author-link=Erica Wagner |title=The constant gardener |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/06/constant-gardener |accessdate=22 April 2020 |work=New Statesman |date=30 June 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nKingsnorth was educated at the [[Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe]], and [[St Anne's College, Oxford]], where he studied modern history. During this period he became involved in the British road protest movement at sites including [[Twyford Down]], [[Solsbury Hill]], and the [[M11 link road protest]] in east London. Much of his writing is focused on issues of place, nature, and environmental concern.<ref name =Endoftheworld>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/its-the-end-of-the-world-as-we-know-it-and-he-feels-fine.html |title=It's the End of the World as We Know It and He Feels Fine |author=Daniel Smith |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 April 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"paulkingsnorth.net\">[http://www.paulkingsnorth.net Paul Kingsnorth's official website]</ref>\n\nIn 1995, he worked briefly on the comment desk of ''[[The Independent]]'', before leaving to join the environmental campaign group EarthAction. He has subsequently worked as [[commissioning editor]] for [[openDemocracy]], as a publications editor for [[Greenpeace]] and, between 1999 and 2001, as deputy editor of ''[[The Ecologist]]''. He was named one of Britain's \"top ten troublemakers\" by the ''[[New Statesman]]'' magazine in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://authors.simonandschuster.co.uk/Paul-Kingsnorth/22566609/biography |title=Paul Kingsnorth author biography |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he was one of the founders of the [[Benny Wenda#Free West Papua Campaign|Free West Papua Campaign]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freewestpapua.org |title=Free West Papua Campaign }}</ref> which campaigns for the secession of the provinces of [[Papua (province)|Papua]] and [[West Papua (province)|West Papua]] from [[Indonesia]], where Kingsnorth was made an [[honorary citizenship|honorary member]] of the [[Lani (ethnic group)|Lani tribe]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paulkingsnorth.net/about.html |title=About Paul Kingsnorth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514082603/http://www.paulkingsnorth.net/about.html |archivedate=14 May 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nKingsnorth announced retirement from journalism in late2007 in a blog post.<ref name =Endoftheworld/> In 2009, with writer and social activist [[Dougald Hine]], Kingsnorth founded the Dark Mountain Project, \"a network of writers, artists, and thinkers who have stopped believing the stories our civilisation tells itself\". Since 2009 it has run a series of summer festivals and smaller events, produced bi-annual anthologies of \"uncivilised\" writing and art, and built up a network of writers and artists across the globe who aim to \"offer up a challenge to the foundations of our civilisation\".<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\" /> He was one of the Project's directors until stepping down in 2017.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Writing ==\n\nAfter travelling through Mexico, West Papau, Genoa in Italy, and Brazil, Kingsnorth wrote his first book in 2003, ''One No, Many Yeses''. His first book, ''One No, Many Yeses''. The book explored how globalisation played a role in destroying historic cultures around the world.<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\" /> It was published in 6 languages in 13 countries.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nKingsnorth's second book, ''Real England'', was published by Portobello Books in 2008. In this book, he reflected on how those same forces of globalisation affected England, his own country.<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\" />\n\nHe has contributed to ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', ''[[Daily Express]]'', ''{{lang|fr|[[Le Monde]]}}'', ''[[New Statesman]]'', ''[[London Review of Books]]'', ''[[Granta]]'', ''[[The Ecologist]]'', ''[[New Internationalist]]'', ''[[The Big Issue]]'', [[Adbusters]], [[BBC Radio 4]], [[BBC Radio 2]], [[BBC Four]], [[ITV Network|ITV]], and [[Resonance FM]].\n\nHis first collection of poetry, ''Kidland and other poems'', was published by Salmon in 2011.<ref name=\"paulkingsnorth.net\"/> In 2012, he won the Wenlock Prize for \"Vodadahue Mountain\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wenlockpoetryfestival.org/complink/poetry-competition-winners-2012.shtml |title=Poetry Competition Winners 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206043657/http://www.wenlockpoetryfestival.org/complink/poetry-competition-winners-2012.shtml |year=2012 |archivedate=6 December 2013 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> His second collection, ''Songs From The Blue River'', was published by Salmon in 2018.\n\nHis first novel, ''[[The Wake (novel)|The Wake]]'', published via [[crowdfunding]] by [[Unbound (publisher)|Unbound]] in April 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unbound.co.uk/books/the-wake |title=''The Wake'' |publisher=[[Unbound (publisher)|Unbound]] }}</ref> was longlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/24/books/man-booker-prize-2014-longlist-announced.html |title=In First, Americans Are Nominated for Booker Prize |author1=Katrin Bennhold |author2=Alexandra Alter |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=23 July 2014 }}</ref> and the [[Folio Prize]], shortlisted for the [[Goldsmiths Prize]], and won the [[Gordon Burn Prize]].<ref name=\"gbprize\">{{cite web |title=Mark Rylance-backed novel wins \u00a35,000 literary prize |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29572691 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=11 October 2014 |date=10 October 2014 }}</ref> Film rights to the novel were sold to a consortium led by the actor [[Mark Rylance]] and the former president of [[HBO Films]] [[Colin Callender]].\n\nKingsnorth's second novel, ''Beast'', was published in 2016 by [[Faber and Faber]] and was shortlisted for the [[Encore Award]] for the Best Second Novel in 2017. His third novel, completing a loose thematic trilogy beginning with ''The Wake'', will also be published by Faber. Announcing the deal, Faber's editorial director, Lee Brackstone, said: \"We are welcoming to Faber a writer who belongs in the tradition of past greats like [[William Golding]], [[Robert Graves]], [[David Peace]] and [[Ted Hughes]]. His sensibility sits comfortably with theirs and his literary achievement could well go on to be their equal. He is that good\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/faber-sign-kingsnorth-wake-trilogy |title=Faber signs Kingsnorth for Wake trilogy |author=Joshua Farrington |work=[[The Bookseller]] |date=4 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n===Nonfiction===\n* ''One No, Many Yeses: a journey to the heart of the global resistance movement'' (2003, Free Press) {{ISBN|0-7432-2027-7}}\n* ''Real England: the battle against the bland'' (2008, Portobello) {{ISBN|1-84627-042-1}}\n* ''Uncivilisation: the Dark Mountain manifesto'' (co-author, 2009, Dark Mountain Project)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dark-mountain.net/about-2/the-manifesto/ |title=Uncivilisation: the Dark Mountain manifesto |publisher=Dark Mountain Project }}</ref>\n* ''Confessions of a Recovering Environmentalist'' (2017, Faber & Faber, Graywolf Press)\n* ''Savage Gods'' (2019, Little Toller, Two Dollar Radio)\n\n===Fiction===\n* ''[[The Wake (novel)|The Wake]]'' (2014, Unbound; 2016, Graywolf Press) {{ISBN|978-1908717863}}\n* ''Beast'' (2016, Faber & Faber; 2017, Graywolf Press) {{ISBN|978-1-55597-779-5}}\n* ''Alexandria'' (2020, Faber & Faber)\n\n===Poetry===\n* ''Kidland and other poems'' (2011, Salmon Poetry) {{ISBN|1-907056-67-X}}\n* ''Songs from the Blue River'' (2018, Salmon Poetry)\n\n===As editor===\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 1'', (2010, Dark Mountain Project)  {{ISBN|0-9564960-0-8}}\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 2'', (2011, Dark Mountain Project)  {{ISBN|0-9564960-1-6}}\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 3'', (2012, Dark Mountain Project)  {{ISBN|0-9564960-2-4}}\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 4'', (2013, Dark Mountain Project)\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 5'', (2014, Dark Mountain Project)\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 6'', (2014, Dark Mountain Project)\n* ''The World-Ending Fire: the essential Wendell Berry'', (2017, Penguin Press) {{ISBN |0-2412792-0-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.paulkingsnorth.net Paul Kingsnorth's website]\n* [https://dark-mountain.net/ The Dark Mountain Project]\n* [http://www.3ammagazine.com/politica/2004/jul/interview_paul_kingsnorth.html Interview with Paul Kingsnorth, from ''3AM'' magazine]\n* [http://www.newstatesman.com/books/2009/09/civilisation-planet-authors ''New Statesman'' review of ''Uncivilisation: the Dark Mountain Manifesto'']\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/its-the-end-of-the-world-as-we-know-it-and-he-feels-fine.html ''New York Times'' Magazine profile, \"It\u2019s the End of the World as We Know It... and He Feels Fine\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingsnorth, Paul}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Worcester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English environmentalists]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Paul Kingsnorth\n| image         = Paul Kingsnorth.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Paul Kingsnorth in 2011\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1972}}\n| birth_place   = [[Worcester]], United Kingdom\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|1972|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Writer and thinker\n| education     = [[St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Novelist, writer, poet, environmentalist\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Kingsnorth''' (born 1972 in [[Worcester]]) is an English writer and thinker. He is a former deputy-editor of ''[[The Ecologist]]'' and a co-founder of the Dark Mountain Project. He lives in [[West Region, Ireland|the west of Ireland]].\n\n==Biography==\nKingsnorth spent his childhood in southern England with two younger brothers (one went on to work with [[Friends of the Earth]], the other for [[Citibank]]). His father was a passionate [[Thatcherite]], a businessman, and a mechanical engineer. Kingsnorth describes his father's background as \"working-class,\" and he says that his father pushed Kingsnorth to go to college. He was the first in his family to do so.<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\">{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Erica| author-link=Erica Wagner |title=The constant gardener |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/06/constant-gardener |accessdate=22 April 2020 |work=New Statesman |date=30 June 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nKingsnorth was educated at the [[Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe]], and [[St Anne's College, Oxford]], where he studied modern history. During this period he became involved in the British road protest movement at sites including [[Twyford Down]], [[Solsbury Hill]], and the [[M11 link road protest]] in east London. Much of his writing is focused on issues of place, nature, and environmental concern.<ref name =Endoftheworld>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/its-the-end-of-the-world-as-we-know-it-and-he-feels-fine.html |title=It's the End of the World as We Know It and He Feels Fine |author=Daniel Smith |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 April 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"paulkingsnorth.net\">[http://www.paulkingsnorth.net Paul Kingsnorth's official website]</ref>\n\nIn 1995, he worked briefly on the comment desk of ''[[The Independent]]'', before leaving to join the environmental campaign group EarthAction. He has subsequently worked as [[commissioning editor]] for [[openDemocracy]], as a publications editor for [[Greenpeace]] and, between 1999 and 2001, as deputy editor of ''[[The Ecologist]]''. He was named one of Britain's \"top ten troublemakers\" by the ''[[New Statesman]]'' magazine in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://authors.simonandschuster.co.uk/Paul-Kingsnorth/22566609/biography |title=Paul Kingsnorth author biography |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he was one of the founders of the [[Benny Wenda#Free West Papua Campaign|Free West Papua Campaign]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freewestpapua.org |title=Free West Papua Campaign }}</ref> which campaigns for the secession of the provinces of [[Papua (province)|Papua]] and [[West Papua (province)|West Papua]] from [[Indonesia]], where Kingsnorth was made an [[honorary citizenship|honorary member]] of the [[Lani (ethnic group)|Lani tribe]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paulkingsnorth.net/about.html |title=About Paul Kingsnorth |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514082603/http://www.paulkingsnorth.net/about.html |archivedate=14 May 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nKingsnorth announced retirement from journalism in late2007 in a blog post.<ref name =Endoftheworld> In 2009, with writer and social activist [[Dougald Hine]], Kingsnorth founded the Dark Mountain Project, \"a network of writers, artists, and thinkers who have stopped believing the stories our civilisation tells itself\". Since 2009 it has run a series of summer festivals and smaller events, produced bi-annual anthologies of \"uncivilised\" writing and art, and built up a network of writers and artists across the globe who aim to \"offer up a challenge to the foundations of our civilisation\".<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\" /> He was one of the Project's directors until stepping down in 2017.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Writing ==\n\nAfter travelling through Mexico, West Papau, Genoa in Italy, and Brazil, Kingsnorth wrote his first book in 2003, ''One No, Many Yeses''. His first book, ''One No, Many Yeses''. The book explored how globalisation played a role in destroying historic cultures around the world.<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\" /> It was published in 6 languages in 13 countries.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nKingsnorth's second book, ''Real England'', was published by Portobello Books in 2008. In this book, he reflected on how those same forces of globalisation affected England, his own country.<ref name=\"NewStatesman-June2016-Gardener\" />\n\nHe has contributed to ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', ''[[Daily Express]]'', ''{{lang|fr|[[Le Monde]]}}'', ''[[New Statesman]]'', ''[[London Review of Books]]'', ''[[Granta]]'', ''[[The Ecologist]]'', ''[[New Internationalist]]'', ''[[The Big Issue]]'', [[Adbusters]], [[BBC Radio 4]], [[BBC Radio 2]], [[BBC Four]], [[ITV Network|ITV]], and [[Resonance FM]].\n\nHis first collection of poetry, ''Kidland and other poems'', was published by Salmon in 2011.<ref name=\"paulkingsnorth.net\"/> In 2012, he won the Wenlock Prize for \"Vodadahue Mountain\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wenlockpoetryfestival.org/complink/poetry-competition-winners-2012.shtml |title=Poetry Competition Winners 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206043657/http://www.wenlockpoetryfestival.org/complink/poetry-competition-winners-2012.shtml |year=2012 |archivedate=6 December 2013 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> His second collection, ''Songs From The Blue River'', was published by Salmon in 2018.\n\nHis first novel, ''[[The Wake (novel)|The Wake]]'', published via [[crowdfunding]] by [[Unbound (publisher)|Unbound]] in April 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unbound.co.uk/books/the-wake |title=''The Wake'' |publisher=[[Unbound (publisher)|Unbound]] }}</ref> was longlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/24/books/man-booker-prize-2014-longlist-announced.html |title=In First, Americans Are Nominated for Booker Prize |author1=Katrin Bennhold |author2=Alexandra Alter |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=23 July 2014 }}</ref> and the [[Folio Prize]], shortlisted for the [[Goldsmiths Prize]], and won the [[Gordon Burn Prize]].<ref name=\"gbprize\">{{cite web |title=Mark Rylance-backed novel wins \u00a35,000 literary prize |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29572691 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=11 October 2014 |date=10 October 2014 }}</ref> Film rights to the novel were sold to a consortium led by the actor [[Mark Rylance]] and the former president of [[HBO Films]] [[Colin Callender]].\n\nKingsnorth's second novel, ''Beast'', was published in 2016 by [[Faber and Faber]] and was shortlisted for the [[Encore Award]] for the Best Second Novel in 2017. His third novel, completing a loose thematic trilogy beginning with ''The Wake'', will also be published by Faber. Announcing the deal, Faber's editorial director, Lee Brackstone, said: \"We are welcoming to Faber a writer who belongs in the tradition of past greats like [[William Golding]], [[Robert Graves]], [[David Peace]] and [[Ted Hughes]]. His sensibility sits comfortably with theirs and his literary achievement could well go on to be their equal. He is that good\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/faber-sign-kingsnorth-wake-trilogy |title=Faber signs Kingsnorth for Wake trilogy |author=Joshua Farrington |work=[[The Bookseller]] |date=4 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n===Nonfiction===\n* ''One No, Many Yeses: a journey to the heart of the global resistance movement'' (2003, Free Press) {{ISBN|0-7432-2027-7}}\n* ''Real England: the battle against the bland'' (2008, Portobello) {{ISBN|1-84627-042-1}}\n* ''Uncivilisation: the Dark Mountain manifesto'' (co-author, 2009, Dark Mountain Project)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dark-mountain.net/about-2/the-manifesto/ |title=Uncivilisation: the Dark Mountain manifesto |publisher=Dark Mountain Project }}</ref>\n* ''Confessions of a Recovering Environmentalist'' (2017, Faber & Faber, Graywolf Press)\n* ''Savage Gods'' (2019, Little Toller, Two Dollar Radio)\n\n===Fiction===\n* ''[[The Wake (novel)|The Wake]]'' (2014, Unbound; 2016, Graywolf Press) {{ISBN|978-1908717863}}\n* ''Beast'' (2016, Faber & Faber; 2017, Graywolf Press) {{ISBN|978-1-55597-779-5}}\n* ''Alexandria'' (2020, Faber & Faber)\n\n===Poetry===\n* ''Kidland and other poems'' (2011, Salmon Poetry) {{ISBN|1-907056-67-X}}\n* ''Songs from the Blue River'' (2018, Salmon Poetry)\n\n===As editor===\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 1'', (2010, Dark Mountain Project)  {{ISBN|0-9564960-0-8}}\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 2'', (2011, Dark Mountain Project)  {{ISBN|0-9564960-1-6}}\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 3'', (2012, Dark Mountain Project)  {{ISBN|0-9564960-2-4}}\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 4'', (2013, Dark Mountain Project)\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 5'', (2014, Dark Mountain Project)\n* ''Dark Mountain: issue 6'', (2014, Dark Mountain Project)\n* ''The World-Ending Fire: the essential Wendell Berry'', (2017, Penguin Press) {{ISBN |0-2412792-0-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.paulkingsnorth.net Paul Kingsnorth's website]\n* [https://dark-mountain.net/ The Dark Mountain Project]\n* [http://www.3ammagazine.com/politica/2004/jul/interview_paul_kingsnorth.html Interview with Paul Kingsnorth, from ''3AM'' magazine]\n* [http://www.newstatesman.com/books/2009/09/civilisation-planet-authors ''New Statesman'' review of ''Uncivilisation: the Dark Mountain Manifesto'']\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/its-the-end-of-the-world-as-we-know-it-and-he-feels-fine.html ''New York Times'' Magazine profile, \"It\u2019s the End of the World as We Know It... and He Feels Fine\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingsnorth, Paul}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Worcester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English environmentalists]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe]]\n